<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,674,2007]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,343,1495,1521]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Etymology:</emphasis>
—This new species of 
<taxonomicName box="[620,737,1496,1521]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Violaceae" genus="Anchietea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[620,737,1496,1521]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Anchietea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is named after Dr. Maria Silvia Ferrucci from Instituto de Botánica del Nordeste, 
<collectingCountry box="[435,558,1533,1559]" name="Argentina" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, a dear friend and brilliant researcher, for her undeniable contribution to botany in 
<collectingCountry box="[268,343,1570,1596]" name="Brazil" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,674,2007]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,536,1607,1633]" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Geographical distribution:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Paula-Souza &amp; Zmarzty" authorityYear="2010" box="[565,813,1608,1633]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Violaceae" genus="Anchietea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="41" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ferrucciae">
<emphasis box="[565,813,1608,1633]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Anchietea ferrucciae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from the “Caatinga domain”, in the region of Abaíra, 
<collectingRegion box="[372,508,1645,1671]" country="Brazil" name="Bahia" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Bahia state</collectingRegion>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[550,629,1645,1671]" name="Brazil" pageId="1" pageNumber="41">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. Even though the Caatingas are in general characterized by a dry deciduous vegetation, the new species occurs especially in non-deciduous formations known as “carrascos” (a closed, tall-shrubby, xerophilous vegetation on quartz sand soils) and on rocky outcrops (map 1).
</paragraph>
